<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>COMMONS TRANSPORT COMMITTEE’S INQUIRY INTO WINTER RESILIENCE IN TRANSPORT</title></head><body><div><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence from the UK Major Ports Group (WRT 009)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Summary</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">1</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The arrangements for winter resilience for transport have improved greatly since the winter of 2009/10. The strategic importance of ports to the UK economy is now much better recognised in planning arrangements. Moreover much of the strategic stockpile of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">salt and grit is being stored at ports which can provide the necessary space, access to supply lines, and handling and distribution expertise. It is essential that ports and main connecting road and rail links continue to be given priority in winter resili</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ence planning. </span></p><p style="margin:11.25pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="color:#333333; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Introduction</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">UKMPG is one of two associations representing ports in the UK.  Our 9 member groups handle over 70 percent of the UK’s international trade by volume, and therefore play a significant role in supporting the UK economy and prom</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">oting exports.  UK ports are privately financed and do not seek any financial help from the taxpayer.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Winter 2009/10</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">During </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">evere winter weather in January 2010</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">some ports began to encounter problems because they were not getting the salt they neede</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">d to keep</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">full operations going. These delivery problems ap</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">peared to be linked to the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Government’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">then </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">prioritisation programme with the Highways Agency and local authorities being given priority for supply over all other customers. On behalf its members </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">UKMPG pressed strongly for ports to be given high priority for salt supplies not only as an essential part of the nation’s transport infrastructure  network but also because of their role in the distribution of imported salt and grit. The Department of Tra</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">nsport acted on these concerns and facilitated the distribution of salt and grit supplies to ports which needed them.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Quarmby</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline"> Report</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">4</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In February 2010 the then Secretary of State for Transport announced that severe winter planning would need to be handled</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> more strategically in future and that the Government would be commissioning a review. In the event this review was carried out by a small team led by David </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Quarmby</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> CBE. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">UKMPG inputted to this review and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">we </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">were pleased to see that the final report publis</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">hed in October 2010 stressed the strategic importance of ports and the strong economic case for maintaining access to ports during </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">severe winter conditions. The main recommendations affecting ports were that </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ports should increase their own pre season salt</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> stock holdings to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">minimise</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> reliance on in season re-stocking</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">there should be a dialogue between ports and relevant highway authorities to ensure there is clear agreement on boundaries and responsibilities</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the relevant access roads should feature on the hi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ghway authorities priority gritting network</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">5</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Ports moved quickly to respond to the report where necessary strengthening the links with highway authorities and also participating in the development of the national </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">strategic </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">salt stockpile managed by the H</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ighways Agency. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Subsequent guidance</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">6</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In Autumn 2011 Department for Transport officials wrote to ports in England inviting them to participate in strengthening contingency planning for the forthcoming winter. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">DfT</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> commended ports for improved performance</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> during the severe weather in the previous winter which had much to do with greater strategic stockpiles of salt and improved planning. In the light of this experience and the implementation of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Quarmby</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> review </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">DfT</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> drew up an overall action plan for port</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s for winter 2011/2. The main new elements of this were</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">A standardized ports industry template on severe weather planning designed to ensure consistency of approach and strengthened co-ordination between the ports sector and the Government. This was drafte</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">d  by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">DfT</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> in consultation with ports and others concerned</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">A full induction and training </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">programme</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> on ports issues for the new DCLG regional resilience teams who had now replaced the Government Office emergency planning network</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Ports were asked to consider </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">how their response to bad weather conditions could be strengthened and to share conclusions with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">DfT</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Ports were strongly encouraged to establish effective links with the new regional resilience teams by for example inviting them on familiarization visits</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">W</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">here needed, ferry ports were asked to establish robust communication links with port operators at the other end of the route to identify potential problems at an early stage</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">7</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Some of the actions that ports themselves have taken to improve winter resilien</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ce on port sites include</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">-    Building new storage facilities for salt and grit</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">-    Acquiring additional snow ploughs and gritting machines</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">-    Trialing de-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">icer</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> sprays on cranes</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">-    Arrangements put in place to lease additional snow clearance </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">vehicles at short notice</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">-   Working closely with the Met Office via Local Resilience Forums to receive bespoke severe weather forecasts and alerts</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">-  Developing Business Resilience and Continuity </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">programmes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to cover all issues connected with extreme wea</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ther including snow and flooding, and carrying out regular test exercises.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Current position</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">8</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Major ports are satisfied that prioritization and planning arrangements are now much improved since the problems encountered in winter 2009/10. Should there be a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> recurrence of severe wintery conditions in winter 2013/4, ports will work closely with customers, stakeholders and other infrastructure providers to ensure that any disruption is kept to a minimum. It is essential that connecting infrastructure to and fro</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">m ports receives priority for snow and ice clearance etc – ports are liaising closely with h</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ighway authorities and Network R</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ail on this. It also remains important that ports have guaranteed salt and grit availability in the event of severe weather. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">O</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ctober 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>